# runtime.log — audit trail for runtime.c
# Format:
#   [function_name]
#   Ghidra: <what the decompiler showed at that address>
#   Rationale: <why implemented this way>
#
# Nothing is implemented until the game crashes and demands it.
# Every entry must have a corresponding Ghidra lookup before implementation.

[psx_set_pad1]
Ghidra: FUN_80019e68 case 3 reads _DAT_1f8001fc directly (scratchpad[0x1FC]).
  Bit masks: &0x80=Up menu, &0x20=Down menu, &0x4008=Cross/Start confirm (1=pressed format).
  FUN_80028D70 (addr=0x80028D70) is the BIOS pad poll — called each frame by FUN_800223e0.
  FUN_8001a51c (game entry after menu confirm) also clears _DAT_1f8001fc=0 at startup.
Rationale: Write current GLFW key state to g_scratch[0x1FC/0x1FD] from psx_present_frame().
  1-frame delay is imperceptible. FUN_80028D70 stub keeps returning v0=0 (no DAT_8009c9d8 noise).
  Key map: GLFW_KEY_UP=0x0080, GLFW_KEY_DOWN=0x0020, GLFW_KEY_ENTER/Z=0x4008, Esc=close.

[FUN_8001EFE8 sound trigger fix]
Ghidra: FUN_8001efe8 contains conditional sound trigger:
  if (DAT_1f8001cd==0x15 && TCB+0x68==0 && frame_counter>0xe)
      FUN_80020af0(0)  → FUN_8006bb4c → sets _DAT_8009e46c bit → activates music sequence
Rationale: Our FUN_8001EFE8 intercept returns 1 (fully handled) so the compiled
  function never runs. The sound trigger was silently skipped. Fix: replicate the
  trigger in the intercept — after 14 FMV ticks with scene=0x15, call FUN_80020AF0(0)
  via psx_dispatch_compiled. Result: KON_lo=0x0003, voices 0+1 key on with
  start=0x48250 ADSR=0x1FC080FF — music plays during WhoopEeCamp FMV and static screen.

[FUN_8004f3dc prim loop guard — fix #40]
Ghidra: FUN_8004f3dc is a sprite/primitive batch builder. Loads loop count from
  entity data: s3 = lh *(*(entity+0x18) + index*4). do-while loop (bne s3, zero)
  decrements s3 and renders one sprite per iteration.
  When entity data is uninitialized (overlay tick functions not yet dispatched),
  count=0 causes 2^32 iterations (~282 seconds). entity=0x00000001 (garbage),
  base=0x08000000 (unmapped mirror). Reads from wild KUSEG addresses (0x243C4FF2 etc.)
  returning 0, building garbage GPU primitives.
Rationale: Add psx_override_dispatch guard — validate count before entering loop.
  If count <= 0, skip entirely (return 1). This prevents the stall without affecting
  correctly-initialized entities. The skip fires ~5 times near f1706-f1722 then stops
  (entity gets properly initialized by overlay dispatch). Result: gameplay runs stable
  at 16ms/frame through 1000+ frames with no stalls.

[FUN_8003B860 — VM conditional branch handler — fix #41]
Ghidra: FUN_8003b860 is a ~264-byte function handling VM opcodes 8-16 (conditional branches).
  Switch on opcode: 8=always, 9/B=flag==0, A/C=flag!=0, D=flag==1, E=flag==2, F=flag!=2, 10=flag!=1.
  Flag at context+0x89, IP at context+0x8A. If condition true → IP = bytecode[IP+1..IP+2].
  If false → IP += 3.
  Context pointer at DAT_8009e458, bytecode base at DAT_8009c974.
Recompiler bug: Split function at 0x8003B880 (beq delay slot). func_8003B860 = 32 bytes (loads
  a0, a3, a1 then returns). func_8003B880 = 280 bytes (actual switch/branch logic, never called).
  MIPS disasm shows: beq at 0x8003B87C, delay slot addiu sp,-8 at 0x8003B880.
Rationale: Override in runtime.c implements full branch evaluation. Reads context+0x89 flag,
  evaluates condition per opcode, updates context+0x8A IP. Returns 1 (fully handled).
  Result: VM completes in 27 ops (was stuck at 500/yield). Intro cutscene sprites spawn.

[FUN_80018248 — entity pending list processor]
Ghidra: Not recognised as function (recompiler missed entry). Called from overlay code
  only (ra=0x80104694, 0x800F3A6C). Manual hex decode of 160 bytes:
  lh v0, scratchpad[0x236]   → count
  blez v0, return_0          → empty list: return 0
  lw a0, scratchpad[0x204]   → list pointer (array of entity ptrs)
  lhu v1, scratchpad[0x1c8]  → flag
  sh count-1, scratchpad[0x236]       ; decrement
  sw pointer+4, scratchpad[0x204]     ; advance
  lw a0, 0(pointer)          → entity_ptr (dereference)
  bne flag&1, 0, L_FLAG
  addiu v0, a0, 0x10         (delay slot)
  flag==0: sw v0, a0[0x40];  v0=a0+0x18;  sw v0, a0[0x44]
  flag!=0: sw v0, a0[0x44];  v0=a0+0x18;  sw v0, a0[0x40]
  returns 0 always (v0 cleared before jr ra)
Rationale: Projectiles/thrown pigs vanish because this function was UNKNOWN — entity
  [0x40]/[0x44] never initialized. Stub implemented in call_by_address: decrements
  scratchpad[0x236] count, advances scratchpad[0x204] pointer by 4, dereferences to
  get entity_ptr, sets entity_ptr[0x40]=entity_ptr+0x10 and [0x44]=entity_ptr+0x18
  (swapped if scratchpad[0x1c8]&1). Returns 0.

[SysEnqIntRP / SysDeqIntRP — C(02)/C(03) BIOS stubs]
Ghidra: FUN_800691d8 (streaming init) calls SysEnqIntRP C(02) with priority=2, queue_ptr=0x8009B2E0.
  Queue struct at 0x8009B2E0: +0 next_ptr, +4 handler_func (FUN_80069058). Priority 2 = CD-ROM IRQ.
  FUN_80068fc4 sets queue struct fields before calling SysEnqIntRP.
  SysDeqIntRP called with same args during teardown (FUN_800691d8 preamble calls SysDeqIntRP C(03)).
Rationale: Was no-op. Now maintains g_int_chains[4] linked list per PS1 BIOS spec.
  SysEnqIntRP: writes old head into queue[0] (next ptr), sets g_int_chains[prio]=queue_ptr.
  SysDeqIntRP: unlinks target entry by walking chain and splicing out (head or interior).
  fire_interrupt_chain() helper walks chain and calls each handler[+4] via call_by_address.
  NOTE: fire_interrupt_chain NOT called from CdRead — FUN_80069058 polls 0x1F801044 (CD hardware)
  in a spin loop when called outside real CD interrupt context → deadlock. The interrupt chain
  is correctly populated (SysEnqIntRP now works) but can only be fired safely when CD hardware
  emulation is present. Lazy injection at 0x800E75CC remains the mechanism for the streaming fix.

[options_screen_cd_streaming]
Ghidra: FUN_80028728 calls FUN_8006a9ec (init streaming struct at 0x8009B3A0) then
  FUN_80068a1c→FUN_800691d8 which calls SysEnqIntRP C(02) to register FUN_80069058
  as the CD-ROM interrupt handler via queue at 0x8009B2E0. FUN_80069058 drives the
  CD streaming state machine; FUN_8006b3b8 sets status byte at 0x8009B3E9=2 after 2+
  CD completion interrupts. The options screen overlay (0x800E75CC) polls FUN_80068aa8
  which reads 0x8009B3E9; returns the byte directly when no busy flags set. Sub_state=0
  handler needs return==2 to advance past the wait loop.
Rationale: SysEnqIntRP was a no-op — CD interrupt FUN_80069058 never registered/fired.
  With no CD-ROM hardware emulation the streaming queue status stays at 0 forever.
  Fix: in INTERP handler for 0x800E75CC, if streaming is enabled (g_ram[0x97548]!=0)
  and status still 0, inject g_ram[0x9B3E9]=2 to simulate CD drive ready.
  Lazy injection is safe: nothing overwrites the byte (no CD interrupts, slot init
  FUN_8006ab4c returns immediately when status==0, never clears our injected value).
  Result: DrawOTag went from 1 nonempty entry to 123 nonempty entries; options screen
  renders correctly with OPTION menu items visible.

[read_word / GPUREAD port 0x1F801810]
Ghidra: N/A (hardware register, not a PS1 binary function).
Rationale: read_word(0x1F801810) returned 0 instead of GPUREAD data.
  The PS1's equipment menu CLUT save/restore sequence uses CPU poll reads from
  port 0x1F801810 to transfer the first N pixels of a VRAM region before the DMA.
  Specifically: game issues C0h VRAMToCPU to fill GPUREAD buffer, CPU reads 8 words
  via LW from 0x1F801810 (pixels 0-15 of terrain CLUT), then DMA reads the remaining
  736 words. On restore: game writes those 8 saved words back via SW to GP0, then DMA
  sends the 736 words. With zero returns the saved values were all 0x0000, corrupting
  the terrain CLUT pixels 0-15 and shifting the entire CLUT by 16 entries.
  Fix: added `if (phys == 0x1F801810) { val = gpu_read_word(); }` in read_word().
  Result: menu close restores correct terrain colors — grass green, no garbling.

[save-flow investigation — session 8 2026-03-11]
Ghidra: 0x8005BA04 — falls within the strlen (FUN_8005B9D4) region; Ghidra did not
  separate it as a function. Bytecode: BEQ $zero,$zero,+26 (unconditional forward
  branch) with delay slot move $v0,$zero → always returns 0.  Not a write-buffer
  setup function; is a utility stub (string/status utility) called during save
  filename preparation.  0x8005BAF0 (strncpy/strcpy area) similarly handles string
  copy operations for the 3-block filename chain.
  INTERP-CALL trace shows: no B(0x35) write() call during any phase of the save
  sequence.  Kernel-area watchpoints (0x0000-0x7FFF) confirmed no BIOS MC buffer
  writes during frames 3400-3510.  Conclusion: game writes MC data via hardware SIO
  (direct register access), not via BIOS B(0x35).  B(0x35) write path in overlay code
  only triggers when O_CREAT fails; our O_CREAT always returns success so that path
  is never taken.
Rationale: Issue #2 "Save Error!" was fixed in session 7 by making FUN_B4CC/nextfile
  return success (faking directory management).  Actual data persistence requires SIO
  MC hardware emulation — deferred.  Diagnostic watchpoints KERN-WW/WH/WB and
  OPEN-DUMP commented out after yielding their data.
